13 [650.058. 1. Notwithstanding the sovereign immunity of the state, any
14 individual who was found guilty of a felony in a Missouri court and was later
15 determined to be actually innocent of such crime may be paid restitution. The
16 individual may receive an amount of one hundred seventy-nine dollars per day
17 for each day of postconviction incarceration for the crime for which the
18 individual is determined to be actually innocent. The petition for the payment
19 of said restitution shall be filed with the sentencing court. For the purposes of
20 this section, the term "actually innocent" shall mean:
21 (1) The individual was convicted of a felony for which a final order of
22 release was entered by the court;
23 (2) All appeals of the order of release have been exhausted;
24 (3) The individual was not serving any term of a sentence for any other
25 crime concurrently with the sentence for which he or she is determined to be
26 actually innocent, unless such individual was serving another concurrent
27 sentence because his or her parole was revoked by a court or the parole board
28 in connection with the crime for which the person has been exonerated.
29 Regardless of whether any other basis may exist for the revocation of the
30 person's probation or parole at the time of conviction for the crime for which
31 the person is later determined to be actually innocent, when the court's or the
32 parole board's sole stated reason for the revocation in its order is the conviction
33 for the crime for which the person is later determined to be actually innocent,
34 such order shall, for purposes of this section only, be conclusive evidence that
35 the persons's probation or parole was revoked in connection with the crime for
36 which the person has been exonerated; and
37 (4) Testing ordered under section 547.035, or testing by the order of
38 any state or federal court, if such person was exonerated on or before August
39 28, 2004, or testing ordered under section 650.055, if such person was or is
40 exonerated after August 28, 2004, or after an evidentiary hearing and finding in
41 a habeas corpus proceeding or a proceeding held pursuant to section 547.031
42 which demonstrates a person's innocence of the crime for which the person is
43 in custody.
